      "text": "Chapter 2 - Improving Neural Networks\n\n1. Vanishing / Exploding Gradient Problem\n    Problem                  →   Solutions \n    Vanishing Gradient     →   ReLU/Leaky ReLU, proper initialization (Xavier/He), Batch Normalization, Skip connections (ResNets), LSTM/GRU for RNNs |\n    Exploding Gradient    →   Gradient clipping, proper initialization, lower learning rate, Batch Normalization |\n    \n2. Weight Initialization\n    → Idea behind weight initialization - we need the variance of the outputs of each layer to be equal to the\nvariance of its inputs,2 and we need the gradients to have equal variance before and\nafter flowing through a layer in the reverse direction\n\n    Technique used to initialize weight is entirely depend on the `Activation Function`\n    1. Zero Initialization:\n        `Tanh, Sigmoid, ReLU`: There is no update at all in the weights because `w` of next hidden layers are in the backpropogation eqn of lower layers.\n    2. Constant Initialization:\n        a. `Tanh, Sigmoid, ReLU`: Except 1st hidden layer, the weights assoicated to the hidden layers acts as `Perceptron` because the output of every\nsingle neuron in there respective hidden layer is same. That menas the gradients wrt those weights also going to be same.\n    3. Random Initialization:\n        a. Smaller values (less than 0.2): Vanishing Gradient\n        b. Largeer values (greater than 0.7): Exploding Gradient\n\n    4. Xavior/Glorat Initialization: Sutaible for Sigmoid and Tanh activation function\n    5. He Initialization: Sutaible for ReLU and its varients\n    6. LeCun Initialization: Sutaible for SELU activation function\n    \n→ When to use Normal varient (Deep Networks) and when uniform (Shallow Networks)?\n \n3. Activation Functions\n    1. Purpose of activation functions and properties of an ideal activation function?\n    2. Disadvantages of Sigmoid and Tanh? Why `Zero Centered` activation functions are preferred?\n    3. Dying ReLU problem and its affct on weights?\n    \n    4. ReLU Varients:\n        1. Leaky ReLU: \n            setting α = 0.2 (a huge leak) seemed to result in better performance than α = 0.01 (a small leak)\n        2. Randomized Leaky ReLU:\n            Act as a regularizer\n        3. PReLU:\n            Better than before but tends to overfit on small datasets\n\n    → ReLU, leaky ReLU, and PReLU all suffer from the fact that they are not smooth functions: their derivatives abruptly change (at z = 0). When we\ndiscussed lasso, this sort of discontinuity can make gradient descent bounce\naround the optimum, and slow down convergence (Unnecessary Computations).\n\n        4. ELU:\n            How it is a sooth function - for alpha = 1 (only)\n            Slow because exp term but Its faster convergence rate during training may compensate for that slow computation.\n        5. SELU:\n             hidden layers use the SELU activation function, then the network will self-normalize\n            Conditions are important befor using SELU\n    \n    → The further varients of ReLU are Non-Monotonic and Non-Convex\n        \n        5. GELU, Swish and Mish: Why would an activation function non-monotonic and non-convex.\n    \n    Q. When to use which activation function?\n        Simple Task: ReLU\n        Faster Convergance: Leaky ReLU\n        Not sure about the value of alpha: PReLU\n        More complex tasks: GELU, Swish, Mish (Transformers and LLM)\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 17.013505933737143,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Chapter 2 - Improving Neural Networks\n\n1. Vanishing / Exploding Gradient Problem\n    Problem                  →   Solutions \n    Vanishing Gradient     →   ReLU/Leaky ReLU, proper initialization (Xavier/He), Batch Normalization, Skip connections (ResNets), LSTM/GRU for RNNs |\n    Exploding Gradient    →   Gradient clipping, proper initialization, lower learning rate, Batch Normalization |\n    \n2. Weight Initialization\n    → Idea behind weight initialization - we need the variance of the outputs of each layer to be equal to the\nvariance of its inputs,2 and we need the gradients to have equal variance before and\nafter flowing through a layer in the reverse direction\n\n    Technique used to initialize weight is entirely depend on the `Activation Function`\n    1. Zero Initialization:\n        `Tanh, Sigmoid, ReLU`: There is no update at all in the weights because `w` of next hidden layers are in the backpropogation eqn of lower layers.\n    2. Constant Initialization:\n        a. `Tanh, Sigmoid, ReLU`: Except 1st hidden layer, the weights assoicated to the hidden layers acts as `Perceptron` because the output of every single neuron in there respective hidden layer is same. That menas the gradients wrt those weights also going to be same.\n    3. Random Initialization:\n        a. Smaller values (less than 0.2): Vanishing Gradient\n        b. Largeer values (greater than 0.7): Exploding Gradient\n\n    4. Xavior/Glorat Initialization: Sutaible for Sigmoid and Tanh activation function\n    5. He Initialization: Sutaible for ReLU and its varients\n    6. LeCun Initialization: Sutaible for SELU activation function\n    \n→ When to use Normal varient (Deep Networks) and when uniform (Shallow Networks)?\n \n3. Activation Functions\n    1. Purpose of activation functions and properties of an ideal activation function?\n    2. Disadvantages of Sigmoid and Tanh? Why `Zero Centered` activation functions are preferred?\n    3. Dying ReLU problem and its affct on weights?\n    \n    4. ReLU Varients:\n        1. Leaky ReLU: \n            setting α = 0.2 (a huge leak) seemed to result in better performance than α = 0.01 (a small leak)\n        2. Randomized Leaky ReLU:\n            Act as a regularizer\n        3. PReLU:\n            Better than before but tends to overfit on small datasets\n\n    → ReLU, leaky ReLU, and PReLU all suffer from the fact that they are not smooth functions: their derivatives abruptly change (at z = 0). When we discussed lasso, this sort of discontinuity can make gradient descent bounce\naround the optimum, and slow down convergence (Unnecessary Computations).\n\n        4. ELU:\n            How it is a sooth function - for alpha = 1 (only)\n            Slow because exp term but Its faster convergence rate during training may compensate for that slow computation.\n        5. SELU:\n             hidden layers use the SELU activation function, then the network will self-normalize\n            Conditions are important befor using SELU\n    \n    → The further varients of ReLU are Non-Monotonic and Non-Convex\n        \n        5. GELU, Swish and Mish: Why would an activation function non-monotonic and non-convex.\n    \n    Q. When to use which activation function?\n        Simple Task: ReLU\n        Faster Convergance: Leaky ReLU\n        Not sure about the value of alpha: PReLU\n        More complex tasks: GELU, Swish, Mish (Transformers and LLM)\n\n\n\n",
